The Chronicle Nqobile Tshili, Chronicle Reporter The  body of the national hero Cde Stanley Nleya has  arrived at his rural home in Masendu, Bulilima District of Matabeleland South. <img class="alignnone size-article-featured-image wp-image-501304" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/06/BA536D40-6325-4168-8DD7-B4BEBF0093D5-680x380.jpeg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/06/BA536D40-6325-4168-8DD7-B4BEBF0093D5-680x380.jpeg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/06/BA536D40-6325-4168-8DD7-B4BEBF0093D5-360x200.jpeg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> The body arrived aboard a Zimbabwe National Army helicopter shortly after 3pm. It was received by the Minister of State for Provincial Affairs Matabeleland South Cde Abednego Ncube. <img class="alignnone size-article-featured-image wp-image-501305" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/06/21A47683-DB04-4DED-AD13-E4E390072009-680x380.jpeg" alt="" width="680" height="380" />Cde Nleya died on Tuesday and will be buried at the National Heroes Acre on Wednesday.
